"name":"Thornton","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places throughout England and Scotland so called, from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The placename is most frequent in northern England, especially Yorkshire, where there are at least 16 possible sources for the surname.","Irish: Anglicized (translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Sceachán</i>’ (see   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."]},{"name":"Thornburrow","meanings":["English:  see  Thornborough  ."]},{"name":"Thornbury","meanings":["English: variant of   Thornberry  .","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thornberry","meanings":["English (southwestern): habitational name from any of various places called Thornbury, in particular Thornbury (Gloucestershire), Thornbury (Herefordshire), or perhaps Thornbury (Devon), or Thornbury in Bradford (Yorkshire). These placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’ or ‘manor’.","English: variant of   Thornber  .","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thornbery","meanings":["English:  see  Thornborough  ."]},{"name":"Thornburgh","meanings":["English (Worcestershire) and Irish: variant of   Thornbury  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Thornborough was born in 1467, in Southampton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir John Thornborough, was 28 and her mother, Alice Laton, was 23. She married Sir Nicholas Griffin about 1506, in Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1467–":"1467–Surnud","1467–Female":"1467–Surnud","1476–1509":"1476–1509","1507–1569":"1507–1569","1440–1531":"1440–1531","1444–1500":"1444–1500","1569":"1569","1467":"1467","about 1506":"umbes 1506","1500":"1500","1444":"1444","1531":"1531","1476":"1476","1440":"1440","1509":"1509","1507":"1507","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England":"Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1467–":"1467–Kuollut","1467–Female":"1467–Kuollut","1476–1509":"1476–1509","1507–1569":"1507–1569","1440–1531":"1440–1531","1444–1500":"1444–1500","1569":"1569","1467":"1467","about 1506":"noin 1506","1500":"1500","1444":"1444","1531":